4 “SECTION 1. ORS 414.665 is amended to read:
5 “414.665. (1) As used in this section, ‘traditional health worker’ includes
6 any of the following:
7 “(a) A community health worker.
8 “(b) A personal health navigator.
9 “(c) A peer wellness specialist.
10 “(d) A peer support specialist.
11 “(e) A doula.
12 “(f) A tribal traditional health worker.
13 “(2) In consultation with the Traditional Health Workers Commission
14 established under ORS 413.600, the Oregon Health Authority, for purposes
15 related to the regulation of traditional health workers, shall adopt by rule:
16 “(a) The qualification criteria, including education and training require-
17 ments, for the traditional health workers utilized by coordinated care or-
18 ganizations, including [distinct qualification criteria for birth doulas and
19 postpartum doulas] qualification criteria for the distinct perinatal doula
20 provider types of birth doula and postpartum doula;
21 “(b) Appropriate professional designations for supervisors of the tradi-

1 tional health workers; and
2 “(c) Processes by which other occupational classifications may be ap-
3 proved to supervise the traditional health workers.
4 “(3) The criteria and requirements established under subsection (2) of this
5 section:
6 “(a) Must be broad enough to encompass the potential unique needs of
7 any coordinated care organization;
8 “(b) Must meet requirements of the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid
9 Services to qualify for federal financial participation; and
10 “(c) May not require certification by the Home Care Commission.
11 “SECTION 2. The Oregon Health Authority shall adopt by rule the
12 qualification criteria for the distinct perinatal doula provider types of
13 birth doula and postpartum doula, as required under the amendments
14 to ORS 414.665 by section 1 of this 2026 Act, no later than January 1,
15 2028.
16 “SECTION 3. ORS 414.667 is repealed.
17 “SECTION 4. ORS 414.668 is amended to read:
18 “414.668. (1) In determining the types and extent of health care and ser-
19 vices to be provided to medical assistance recipients under ORS 414.065, the
20 Oregon Health Authority and a coordinated care organization shall ensure
21 that recipients have access to services provided by doulas[, lactation counse-
22 lors and lactation educators].
23 “(2) The services described in subsection (1) of this section must:
24 “(a) Include a minimum of 24 hours of services, in addition to labor and
25 delivery services, regardless of birth outcome, with an option for the au-
26 thority or a coordinated care organization to approve additional hours based
27 on need;
28 “(b) Be sufficient to support recipients’ robust maternal health and sup-
29 port positive birth outcomes; and
30 “(c) Be provided:
